Answering my own questions. Yes this code still works and yes the CF uses the modprefix as defined in config.cpp as the first parameter. If you use other mods to learn it can be confusing because vanilla does it differently and not all mods use CF.  To be clear, this code works. ```modded class MissionBase
{
    void MissionBase() {
        GetRPCManager().AddRPC("YOURMODPREFIX", "TestRPCFunction", this, SingleplayerExecutionType.Both);
    }
    void TestRPCFunction(CallType type, ParamsReadContext ctx, PlayerIdentity sender, Object target) {
        Param1<string> data;
        if (!ctx.Read(data)) return;

        if (type == CallType.Server) {
            Print("Function called on server!");
        }
        else {
            Print("Function called on client!");
        }
    }
    override void OnKeyPress(int key) {
        Print("Key Press Detected");
        super.OnKeyPress(key);
        if (key == KeyCode.KC_K) {
            GetRPCManager().SendRPC("YOURMODPREFIX", "TestRPCFunction", new Param1<string>("Hello, World!"));  
        }
    }
}``` But there is one little thing that tripped me up and might trip up a fellow noob. The code in `OnKeyPress` is called from the client. Therefore, `TestRPCFunction` runs on the server. This means that you won't see the console message in the workbench debugger unless you have selected "debug server" from the debug menu.

